(63, 1, 73, 'Stage 2 Carer Post-Trial', 'Stage 2 Carer Post-Trial', 'Stage 2 Carer Post-Trial', 'User Evaluation of an Obstacle Alerting System\r\nVerbally administered Carer post-trial questionnaire\r\n\r\nThe Obstacle Alerting System – A reminder of what it was meant to do.\r\nThe goal of the obstacle alerting system is to give the user more confidence, better control, improved safety, easier to drive and better performance from the PWC\r\nThe obstacle alerting system attached to the powered chair will have the following features.\r\nSensors: To detect objects to the front, sides and rear of the chair.\r\nThere may be some objects that they may not detect very well e.g. Glass or soft furnishings.\r\nThere may be some lighting conditions where they are less reliable e.g. bright sunlight.\r\n\r\nFeedback to the user:\r\nInformation about the proximity of objects will be provided in three ways.\r\nAudio, Visual and Haptic.\r\nThe user can turn on and off each option. The user can select any combination of these feedback options.\r\n\r\n1. Audio Feedback: \r\nThere will be options of a; \r\n- warning “beep” indicating the presence of an object. The user can then look at the display to see where this object is.\r\n- voice giving warning of the location of the object. \r\nThe audio feedback can be turned off.\r\n\r\n2. Visual Display Feedback:\r\nThe display will show where the object is and give an indication of how close it is to the chair.\r\nThe display can be used in conjunction with the warning beep or voice.\r\nThe display can be turned off. \r\nDriving At High Speeds: For safety reasons the display will automatically turn off when you are driving above an agreed speed. \r\nA reversing camera and display: This feedback is similar to those used in cars. In this trial the reversing camera will have its own display. The display is only activated when the chair is reversing.\r\n\r\n3. Haptic Feedback:\r\nA small vibrator is built into the joystick. This will vibrate as the object is approached.\r\nThe user can then look at the display or listen to the audio feedback to get more information about the location of that object.\r\nHaptic feedback can also be turned off.\r\nWe can now reflect on how well the system met your expectations, how it might benefit other users and carers and how the system could be improved.', 'User Evaluation of an Obstacle Alerting System\r\nVerbally administered Carer post-trial questionnaire\r\n\r\nThe Obstacle Alerting System – A reminder of what it was meant to do.\r\nThe goal of the obstacle alerting system is to give the user more confidence, better control, improved safety, easier to drive and better performance from the PWC\r\nThe obstacle alerting system attached to the powered chair will have the following features.\r\nSensors: To detect objects to the front, sides and rear of the chair.\r\nThere may be some objects that they may not detect very well e.g. Glass or soft furnishings.\r\nThere may be some lighting conditions where they are less reliable e.g. bright sunlight.\r\n\r\nFeedback to the user:\r\nInformation about the proximity of objects will be provided in three ways.\r\nAudio, Visual and Haptic.\r\nThe user can turn on and off each option. The user can select any combination of these feedback options.\r\n\r\n1. Audio Feedback: \r\nThere will be options of a; \r\n- warning “beep” indicating the presence of an object. The user can then look at the display to see where this object is.\r\n- voice giving warning of the location of the object. \r\nThe audio feedback can be turned off.\r\n\r\n2. Visual Display Feedback:\r\nThe display will show where the object is and give an indication of how close it is to the chair.\r\nThe display can be used in conjunction with the warning beep or voice.\r\nThe display can be turned off. \r\nDriving At High Speeds: For safety reasons the display will automatically turn off when you are driving above an agreed speed. \r\nA reversing camera and display: Th