(64, 1, 74, 'Stage 2 Carer Pre-Trial', 'Stage 2 Carer Pre-Trial', 'Stage 2 Carer Pre-Trial', 'User Evaluation of an Obstacle Alerting System\r\nVerbally administered Carer pre-trial questionnaire\r\n\r\nThe Obstacle Alerting System – A reminder of what it was meant to do.\r\nThe goal of the obstacle alerting system is to give the user more confidence, better control, and better performance from the PWC.\r\nThe carer’s role is to provide feedback about their experiences and observation of the user’s experiences with the Obstacle Alerting System and to suggest ways in which it can be improved.\r\n\r\nThe obstacle alerting system attached to the powered chair will have the following features.\r\nSensors: To detect objects to the front, sides and rear of the chair.\r\nThere may be some objects that they may not detect very well e.g. Glass or soft furnishings.\r\nThere may be some lighting conditions where they are less reliable e.g. bright sunlight.\r\nFeedback: Information to the user about the proximity of obstacles using visual, audio and haptic feedback.\r\nA reversing camera. This feedback is similar to those used in cars. In this trial the reversing camera had its own display.\r\nYour observations and feedback during and after the trial will be very valuable.', 'User Evaluation of an Obstacle Alerting System\r\nVerbally administered Carer pre-trial questionnaire\r\n\r\nThe Obstacle Alerting System – A reminder of what it was meant to do.\r\nThe goal of the obstacle alerting system is to give the user more confidence, better control, and better performance from the PWC.\r\nThe carer’s role is to provide feedback about their experiences and observation of the user’s experiences with the Obstacle Alerting System and to suggest ways in which it can be improved.\r\n\r\nThe obstacle alerting system attached to the powered chair will have the following features.\r\nSensors: To detect objects to the front, sides and rear of the chair.\r\nThere may be some objects that the